Claims CLAIMS  What is claimed is: 1. A polymeric substrate that is incompatible with photolithography conditions, at least a portion of a surface of which comprises a material suitable for cell attachment, in a pattern that is raised above the surface of said substrate. 2. The polymeric substrate of claim 1, wherein the raised pattern comprises the polymer of said polymeric substrate. 3. The polymeric substrate of claim 1 or 2, wherein the raised pattern comprises at least one cell-binding or cell-adhesive material. 4. The polymeric substrate of any one of claims 1 to 3 which is incompatible with photolithography conditions due to one or more incompatibilities selected from the group consisting of temperature incompatibility, solvent incompatibility, reagent incompatibility, and surface geometry incompatibility. 5. The polymeric substrate of claim 4, wherein said surface geometry incompatibility comprises curvature. 6. The polymeric substrate of claim 5, which comprises a curved surface selected from the group consisting of inward-curving concave surfaces and outward-curving convex surfaces. 7. The polymeric substrate of any one of claims 1 to 6, wherein the polymeric substrate is in the form of a tube or a tube-like structure and the raised-patterned surface is on the interior of the tube or tube-like structure. 8. The polymeric substrate of claim 7, wherein said tube or tube-like structure comprises a rolled species, a rolled-up system, a preformed tube, or a species of similar geometry. 9. A method of patterning a surface of a polymeric substrate which is incompatible with photolithography conditions, comprising the steps of a) providing a shadow mask, b) applying the shadow mask to a surface of said polymeric substrate to form a masked substrate, 

 c) applying pressure to the shadow mask surface of the masked substrate, optionally with heating sufficient to form a phase transition in the polymer of said polymeric substrate, d) optionally, cooling said masked substrate, and e) removing the mask to reveal a patterned polymeric surface. 10. The method of claim 9, wherein said polymeric substrate is incompatible with photolithography conditions due to one or more incompatibilities selected from the group consisting of temperature incompatibility, solvent incompatibility, reagent incompatibility, and surface geometry incompatibility. 11. The method of claim 10, wherein said surface geometry incompatibility comprises curvature. 12. The method of claim 11, where the patterning is on the inside surface of a tube, a tube-like substrate, or a folded substrate. 13. The method of claim 12, wherein said tube or tube-like substrate comprises a rolled species, a rolled-up system, a preformed tube, or a species of similar geometry. 14. The method of any one of claims 9 to 13, wherein said polymeric substrate is a preformed tube having patterning on the inside surface. 15. A method of preparing a shadow mask for patterning the inside surface of a polymeric tube which is incompatible with photolithography conditions, comprising the steps of a) providing a coupon of polymer having a thickness of about 10 microns to about 120 microns, and having appropriate dimensions to completely cover the inside surface of a polymeric tube, and b) ablation of said coupon to remove selected segments of the polymer, providing a desired pattern; wherein the coupon polymer is adherent to said polymeric tube such that the peel strength is less than the tensile strength of said coupon polymer and said polymeric tube. 16. The method of claim 15, wherein said ablation comprises laser ablation. 17. The method of claim 15 or 16, wherein said polymeric tube is incompatible with photolithography conditions due to one or more incompatibilities selected from the group consisting of temperature incompatibility, solvent incompatibility, reagent incompatibility, and surface geometry incompatibility. 18. The method of claim 17, wherein said surface geometry incompatibility comprises curvature. 19. A construct which supports cell attachment and alignment, comprising: a) a substrate which is incompatible with photolithography conditions; b) a patterned coating of a metal alkoxide, oxide or mixed oxide-alkoxide disposed thereon; and c) a phosphonic acid covalently attached to b), which phosphonic acid contains functionality adapted for cell binding. 20. The construct of claim 19, further comprising cells attached thereto. 21. The construct of claim 19 or 20, further comprising an aligned extracellular matrix (ECM). 22. The construct of any one of claims 19 to 21, wherein said substrate is incompatible with photolithography conditions due to one or more incompatibilities selected from the group consisting of temperature incompatibility, solvent incompatibility, reagent incompatibility, and surface geometry incompatibility. 23. The construct of claim 22, wherein said surface geometry incompatibility comprises curvature. 24. The construct of any one of claims 19 to 23, wherein said phosphonic acid comprises one or more functional groups selected from the group consisting of polyol moieties, sugar alcohol moieties, hydroxyl functional groups, amino functional groups, carboxylic acid functional groups, carboxylate ester functional groups, phosphonic acid functional groups, phosphonate functional groups, ether functional groups, alkyne functional groups, azide functional groups and thiol functional groups. 25. The construct of claim 24, wherein said phosphonic acid is 1,4- butanediphosphonic acid. 26. The construct of any one of claims 19 to 25, wherein said substrate comprises a polymer selected from the group consisting of polyamides, polyurethanes, polyureas, polyesters, polyketones, polyimides, polysulfides, polysulfoxides, polysulfones, polythiophenes, polypyridines, polypyrroles, polyethers, silicone (polysiloxanes), polysaccharides, fluoro-polymers, epoxies, aramides, amides, imides, polypeptides, polyolefins, polyethylene, polystyrene, poly-propylene, liquid crystal polymers, thermoplastics, polyvinyls, poly(vinyl alcohol), polyacrylics, polyacrylates, poly(acrylic acid), polycarbonates, polytetrafluoroethylene (PTFE), polyethylene terephthalate (PET), polyvinylpyrrolidone), poly(2-hydroxyethyl methacrylate), poly(N-vinylpyrrolidone), poly(methyl methacrylate), polyethylene-co-vinyl acetate), poly(methacrylic acid), polylactides (PLA), polyglycolides (PGA), poly(lactide-co-glycolides) (PLGA), polylactones, polyanhydrides, polyphosphazenes, polyorthoesters, polycaprolactone fumarate (PCLF), oligo-(polyethylene glycol) fumarate (OPF), PEDOT:PSS, poly(ethylene oxide), poly(ethylene glycol), cross-linked poly(acrylic acid), poly(acrylamides), sucrose, carbohydrate glass, silk, collagen, alginate, chitosan, and chondroitin, copolymers and derivatives thereof, and composites including these polymers. 27. The construct of claim 26, wherein said substrate polymer comprises PCLF or OPF. 28. The construct of any one of claims 19 to 27, where said patterned coating is on the inside surface of a tube, a tube-like substrate, or a folded substrate. 29. The construct of claim 28, wherein said tube or tube-like substrate comprises a rolled species, a rolled-up system, a preformed tube, or a species of similar geometry. 30. A method of preparing a construct which supports cell attachment and alignment, said method comprising: a) providing a substrate which is incompatible with photolithography conditions; 

 b) preparing a shadow mask template consisting of a material which is adherent to said substrate such that the peel strength is less than the tensile strength of said shadow mask and substrate material; and c) adhering said shadow mask template to said substrate to form a substrate-mask ensemble. 31. The method of claim 30, further comprising: d) exposing said substrate-mask ensemble to a metal alkoxide to form a treated substrate-mask ensemble; e) warming the treated ensemble and removing said mask from said treated substrate-mask ensemble to form a metal oxide/alkoxide patterned surface; and f) covalently attaching to said patterned surface a phosphonic acid containing functionality adapted for cell binding, to form said construct. 32. The method of claim 30, further comprising: d) exposing said substrate-mask ensemble to a cell-adhesive biomaterial to form a treated substrate-mask ensemble; and e) removing said mask from said treated substrate-mask ensemble to form a cell- adhesive patterned surface to form said construct. 33. The method of claim 31 or 32, further comprising: attaching cells to said construct. 34. The method of claim 31 or 32, further comprising: incubating said construct to form an aligned extracellular matrix (ECM). 35. The method of any one of claims 30 to 34, wherein said substrate is incompatible with photolithography conditions due to one or more incompatibilities selected from the group consisting of temperature incompatibility, solvent incompatibility, reagent incompatibility, and surface geometry incompatibility. 36. The method of claim 35, wherein said surface geometry incompatibility comprises curvature. 37. The method of claim 36, wherein said substrate comprises a tube, a tube-like, or a folded structure and wherein the inside surface of the substrate is patterned. 38. The method of claim 37, wherein said tube or tube-like structure comprises a rolled species, a rolled-up system, a preformed tube, or a structure of similar geometry. 39. The method of claim 31, wherein said phosphonic acid comprises one or more functional groups selected from the group consisting of polyol moieties, sugar alcohol moieties, hydroxyl functional groups, amino functional groups, carboxylic acid functional groups, carboxylate ester functional groups, phosphonic acid functional groups, phosphonate functional groups, ether functional groups, alkyne functional groups, azide functional groups and thiol functional groups. 40. The method of claim 39, wherein said phosphonic acid is 1,4-butanediphosphonic acid. 41. The method of any one of claims 30 to 40, wherein said substrate comprises a polymer selected from the group consisting of polyamides, polyurethanes, polyureas, polyesters, polyketones, polyimides, polysulfides, polysulfoxides, polysulfones, polythiophenes, polypyridines, polypyrroles, polyethers, silicone (polysiloxanes), polysaccharides, fluoro-polymers, epoxies, aramides, amides, imides, polypeptides, polyolefins, polyethylene, polystyrene, poly-propylene, liquid crystal polymers, thermoplastics, polyvinyls, poly(vinyl alcohol), polyacrylics, polyacrylates, poly(acrylic acid), polycarbonates, polytetrafluoroethylene (PTFE), polyethylene terephthalate (PET), polyvinylpyrrolidone), poly(2-hydroxyethyl methacrylate), poly(N-vinylpyrrolidone), poly(methyl methacrylate), polyethylene-co-vinyl acetate), poly(methacrylic acid), polylactides (PLA), polyglycolides (PGA), poly(lactide-co-glycolides) (PLGA), polylactones, polyanhydrides, polyphosphazenes, polyorthoesters, polycaprolactone fumarate (PCLF), oligo-(polyethylene glycol) fumarate (OPF), PEDOT:PSS, poly(ethylene oxide), poly(ethylene glycol), cross-linked poly(acrylic acid), poly(acrylamides), sucrose, carbohydrate glass, silk, collagen, alginate, chitosan, and chondroitin, copolymers and derivatives thereof, and composites including these polymers. 42. The method of claim 41, wherein said substrate polymer comprises PCLF or OPF. 43. The method of claim 42, wherein said substrate polymer is PCLF. 44. A construct which supports cell attachment and alignment, comprising: a) a substrate which is incompatible with photolithography conditions; and b) a patterned coating of a cell-adhesive compound comprising fibronectin disposed thereon. 45. The construct of claim 44, further comprising cells attached thereto. 46. The construct of claim 44 or 45, further comprising an aligned extracellular matrix (ECM).
